---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'Agent Communication Bus — Real-Time Agent-to-Agent Messaging',
  description: 'The Signal Bus lets AI agents communicate in real time via structured message broadcasting. Channel-based, project-scoped, SSE-powered — for coordinated multi-agent workflows.',
  url: 'https://telepathine.ai/agent-communication-bus',
  author: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'ArtemisAI',
  },
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Agent Communication Bus"
  description="The Signal Bus lets AI agents communicate in real time via structured message broadcasting. Channel-based, project-scoped coordination for multi-agent workflows."
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
  canonicalUrl="https://telepathine.ai/agent-communication-bus"
>
  <section class="content-layer px-4 pb-8 pt-24 sm:px-6 sm:pt-32 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-widest" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Guide</p>
      <h1 class="mt-2">Agent Communication Bus</h1>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg" style="color: var(--text-muted);">When your agents can talk to each other, they stop duplicating work and start coordinating. The Signal Bus is the real-time communication layer for multi-agent systems.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="content-layer section-divider px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8">
      <div>
        <h2>The coordination problem</h2>
        <p class="mt-3" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Modern AI development often uses multiple agents: one for architecture reviews, one for implementation, one for testing. But these agents can't share findings in real time. They operate in isolation — even when working on the same project.</p>
        <p class="mt-3" style="color: var(--text-muted);">An agent communication bus solves this. Agents broadcast messages on channels. Other agents subscribe to those channels. Findings, decisions, and alerts flow between agents without human mediation.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2>How the Signal Bus works</h2>
        <div class="mt-6 space-y-6">
          <div class="flex gap-4">
            <div class="step-circle">1</div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold" style="color: var(--text);">Register an agent</h3>
              <p class="mt-1 text-sm" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Each agent identifies itself with a name and role. Registration creates a persistent identity on the bus.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-4">
            <div class="step-circle">2</div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold" style="color: var(--text);">Subscribe to channels</h3>
              <p class="mt-1 text-sm" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Channels are named communication paths — like a project's #architecture channel or #bugs channel. Agents subscribe to the channels relevant to their work.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-4">
            <div class="step-circle">3</div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold" style="color: var(--text);">Broadcast messages</h3>
              <p class="mt-1 text-sm" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Agents send structured messages to channels. Messages are delivered via Server-Sent Events (SSE) to all subscribers in real time.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-4">
            <div class="step-circle">4</div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold" style="color: var(--text);">Memory Bridge persists messages</h3>
              <p class="mt-1 text-sm" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Bus messages are automatically persisted as observations in your project memory. Future context injections include relay history — so even agents that weren't subscribed can catch up.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2>Use cases</h2>
        <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
          <div class="surface-card p-4">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-sm" style="color: var(--text);">Architecture + Implementation</h3>
            <p class="mt-1 text-sm" style="color: var(--text-muted);">An architecture reviewer broadcasts design decisions. The implementation agent receives them and adjusts its approach accordingly.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="surface-card p-4">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-sm" style="color: var(--text);">Bug triage swarms</h3>
            <p class="mt-1 text-sm" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Multiple agents investigate different facets of a bug. Findings converge on a shared channel. The fix agent gets the complete picture.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="surface-card p-4">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-sm" style="color: var(--text);">Cross-project awareness</h3>
            <p class="mt-1 text-sm" style="color: var(--text-muted);">An agent working on shared library changes broadcasts breaking changes. Service agents across projects receive the alert and adapt.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="surface-card p-4">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-sm" style="color: var(--text);">Human-in-the-loop review</h3>
            <p class="mt-1 text-sm" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Humans subscribe to agent channels too. Monitor decisions, intervene when needed, and let agents handle routine coordination autonomously.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2>Bus architecture</h2>
        <div class="surface-panel p-6 mt-4">
          <pre class="overflow-x-auto text-sm" style="color: var(--text-copy);"><code>{`┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐
│ Agent A  │  │ Agent B  │  │ Agent C  │
│ (Claude) │  │ (Cursor) │  │ (Gemini) │
└─────┬────┘  └─────┬────┘  └─────┬────┘
      │             │             │
      ▼             ▼             ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│           Signal Bus                │
│  ┌─────────┐ ┌───────────────────┐  │
│  │ #arch   │ │ #bugs            │  │
│  │ channel │ │ channel          │  │
│  ├─────────┤ ├───────────────────┤  │
│  │ #deploy │ │ Memory Bridge     │  │
│  │ channel │ │ → observations   │  │
│  └─────────┘ └───────────────────┘  │
│                                     │
│  SSE delivery · Project-scoped      │
│  Message persistence                │
└─────────────────────────────────────┘`}</code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2>Getting started</h2>
        <pre class="mt-4 overflow-x-auto rounded-lg p-4 text-sm" style="background: var(--bg-code); border: 1px solid var(--line); color: var(--text-copy);"><code>{`# Broadcast a message on a channel
curl -X POST https://api.telepathine.ai/v1/bus/messages \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $TELEPATHINE_API_KEY" \\
  -d '{
    "channel": "architecture",
    "agent": "reviewer",
    "message": "Decided on event-sourcing for audit log",
    "project": "my-service"
  }'

# Subscribe to a channel (SSE stream)
curl -N https://api.telepathine.ai/v1/bus/channels/architecture/stream \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $TELEPATHINE_API_KEY"`}</code></pre>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm" style="color: var(--text-muted);">The Signal Bus is available on Ignite, Blaze, and Enterprise plans. Spark users can upgrade when they need multi-agent coordination.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="surface-panel p-6 text-center">
        <h3>Let your agents coordinate</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Signal Bus: real-time agent communication with memory persistence built in.</p>
        <div class="mt-4 flex items-center justify-center gap-4">
          <a href="/pricing" class="btn-accent">See Plans →</a>
          <a href="/features" class="btn-ghost">All Features</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
